<br>
EzCode only matters when it comes to putting in formatting, like bold or italics. If you just type your stuff normally (double-spacing for paragraphs), it will post that way.<br>
<br>
Starting with a shallow backstory is FINE! You don't have to show up with a full history. Many of us start with just a few ideas about our character (&quot;I'm a really naive and helpful guy&quot; or &quot;I am terrified bugs&quot; or whatever), and then develop our story as we learn about the world and interact with others.<br>
<br>
The newbie areas are, in general, worse than the rest of the world for finding good players. Yes, there are ALOT of good players in the newbie areas, but that is also where you find the bored d00dz who are just trying out the server. You made a good start by posting here - I have met alot of people in-game because I got active on the boards that I would never have met otherwise (I am still a pretty new player on FV). Keep trying, it DOES get better.<br>
<br>
I am a magician also, so I can give you some tips on helping others. If someone is obviously overwhelmed and dying, you can usually send in your pet or nuke to pull a monster or two off. Make sure you say &quot;I hope I didn't interfere, you looked like you were getting swarmed&quot; or something like that when the battle is over. People obviously running to the guards usually appreciate it very much if you pull off a monster or two. If they are jerks about you helping, chances are they won't last long here anyhow, so you can just ignore them and move on with your game.<br>
<br>
You, as a magician, have infinite numbers of summonable bandaids! Get that bind wounds skill up! You can bind someone while they fight, as long as they don't run away. Tell them &quot;hold still, I am bandaging&quot; and most will stay. If you see someone drop, but they're not yet dead (it won't say &quot;Soandso's corpse&quot; yet, and the monster will still be attacking their body), you can send it your pet to fight and bind them so they don't die.<br>
<br>
At level 8 (I think) you get your first damage shield. You can toss that on people fighting, and it won't aggro anything on you or take away their experience in the fight. It DOES give you faction changes - so be careful about tossing it on people fighting things that you don't want bad faction with.<br>
<br>
You can also offer people you meet your summoned items - you get bandaids, bags, food, water, and weapons (all mage weapons are magic, too!). You get your first focus item (the necklace) at level 4, and just about everyone loves those. Summoned items are actually valued here. Don't forget you can equip people's pets, too!<br>
<br>
About duelling - it doesn't cost you experience to lose (to address the game mechanic issue). You can always roleplay being afraid to fight, if you don't want to. Or you can /duel someone just on the principle of the thing, knowing you will lose. I /duelled Gore (level god Iksar) when I was level 8? maybe, because he had been killing gnomish clockworks the day before and I saw him picking on those nice elf guards the next day. I /ruded him, he challenged me, I accepted, I died real fast. And then I had a great roleplay session (no common language, even!) with the elven cleric who rez'd me for standing up for the elven guards. I'd /rude that mean lizard if I ever ran into him again, too! Bad lizard!<br>
<br>
Welcome to Firiona Vie, by the way!<br>
